package to force all conflicts to become errors. So what does that mean? It basically, we can

00:06:49.779 --> 00:06:56.739
explicitly check for conflicts with, when we load the Tidyverse, with existing loaded packages. And

00:06:56.739 --> 00:07:01.540
in this case, I'm loading the Tidyverse before loading any other things. So this is the conflicts

00:07:01.540 --> 00:07:07.140
with base R, basically, or the stats package in this case. Filter and lag are functions that exist

00:07:07.140 --> 00:07:15.220
there that Tidyverse is overwriting or dplyr. If the conflict resolution with base R looks

00:07:15.220 --> 00:07:21.459
something like this, it just gives precedence to the most recently loaded package. So if I

00:07:21.459 --> 00:07:26.980
have not loaded the Tidyverse yet, and I try to do something like filter for the species where

00:07:26.980 --> 00:07:34.420
the penguins are Adélie, it will give me an error that's not like I can't find the filter function.

00:07:34.420 --> 00:07:40.179
In fact, it's giving me the error of what would this sort of expression passed

00:07:40.179 --> 00:07:47.700
onto stats filter would look like. After loading the Tidyverse, base R will silently use the last

00:07:47.700 --> 00:07:54.260
loaded package, and things work nicely. Until they don't, I suppose. With conflicted, what you can

00:07:54.260 --> 00:07:59.380
see is that if that package is loaded, the error is a little bit different. It is saying that I am

00:07:59.380 --> 00:08:07.459
not going to just use one of the ones. It's saying there are two packages that have the filter function,

