or you can say I'm going to use filter a lot. I know that I want the dplyr filter going forward,

00:08:28.179 --> 00:08:35.380
so for this session, I want to prefer dplyr filter. So from that point onwards in my session,

00:08:35.380 --> 00:08:42.020
it is going to use the dplyr filter. So this is making things a lot more explicit,

00:08:42.020 --> 00:08:48.020
which, when things are going fine, is almost overhead, frankly. But when they're not, it's

00:08:48.020 --> 00:08:54.099
actually one of the more annoying, I think, error messages to sort of figure out when you're using

00:08:54.099 --> 00:09:00.099
the wrong function from a package you didn't intend to. And this can grow to be an even bigger

00:09:00.099 --> 00:09:05.539
problem when you have lots of packages that might have sort of named conflicts. So a little bit of

00:09:05.539 --> 00:09:11.700
teaching tip around this. I said that loading the tidyverse message got even longer now,

00:09:11.700 --> 00:09:17.780
and I did hear the sigh, and I am with you on that. But I think that it is important to show

00:09:17.780 --> 00:09:23.299
these startup messages in the teaching materials and not hide them, especially if you teach with

00:09:23.299 --> 00:09:29.700
slides. I know that it is so tempting to hide them because they take up so much space, but I think

00:09:29.700 --> 00:09:34.260
it's important to address them early on because, first of all, you want to model good behavior. You

00:09:34.260 --> 00:09:39.460
can't ask your students to read error messages if you don't read them yourself, or any messages for

00:09:39.460 --> 00:09:44.979
that matter. So it requires, it encourages reading and understanding messages, warnings, and errors,

00:09:44.979 --> 00:09:50.659
and what the distinction between them are. And also it helps during hard to debug situations

00:09:50.659 --> 00:09:55.859
that result from Basar's silent conflict resolution. That's definitely going to be something that will

00:09:55.859 --> 00:10:02.099
be even harder for especially new learners. That being said, do show your students how to hide those,

00:10:02.099 --> 00:10:08.340
particularly at like an editing or polishing a document stage. All right, so let's talk about

