join. I'm actually wondering the process that happens behind the scenes of how you decide like

00:48:26.820 --> 00:48:31.939
what is going to be like available function, what's going to be available argument. I wonder

00:48:31.939 --> 00:48:39.139
if you can share a bit of the process. Yeah. So there are a few ways that this happens. Sometimes

00:48:39.139 --> 00:48:45.139
it is a sort of a minor fix and one person in the team implements it and another reviews it because

00:48:45.139 --> 00:48:50.260
like there was an issue open and a few thumbs up and a few people chiming in saying yes, this would

00:48:50.260 --> 00:48:56.820
be good. But for example, for something like this and also this enhancement for the separate

00:48:56.820 --> 00:49:03.540
functions went hand in hand with one that I didn't get into detail, which was the alignment

00:49:03.540 --> 00:49:09.540
of functions in string R and tidy R that deal basically with character strings. Because if you

00:49:09.540 --> 00:49:16.260
think about this whole separate thing is about splitting character strings oftentimes. There is

00:49:16.340 --> 00:49:26.500
a process that is sort of inspired by pythons, I believe peps, where you sort of like propose

00:49:27.379 --> 00:49:34.179
an enhancement or a change or an update and then you do a write-up. So someone from the tidyverse

00:49:34.179 --> 00:49:41.139
teams does a write-up. The repo is called tidyups, so it's under the tidyverse organization. And so

00:49:41.139 --> 00:49:47.699
some ideas develop there and we actually, we have weekly meetings where someone will present on it

00:49:47.699 --> 00:49:51.939
and especially for something like this, I'm making up a number, but I wouldn't be surprised if this

00:49:51.939 --> 00:49:56.820
was like three or four separate like presentations where we discuss what is the right syntax, what's

00:49:56.820 --> 00:50:03.780
the right API for it, what RH cases we're missing or not missing. And then, you know, there's a

00:50:03.780 --> 00:50:09.300
proposal that's written that a couple people on the team will be like, okay, I'm sort of a signatory

00:50:09.300 --> 00:50:16.979
to this proposal. I can see how this is valuable. And then for big updates like this one and also

00:50:16.979 --> 00:50:23.699
many of the dplyr updates, one of the team members will often write a blog post sort of soliciting

00:50:23.699 --> 00:50:30.260
feedback from the community. So while the package is still in development, sort of soliciting feedback

00:50:30.979 --> 00:50:37.060
and then if sort of like that feedback is feeling like, okay, there's enough, like people can sort

00:50:37.060 --> 00:50:44.100
of see how this would improve their workflows, ultimately things get merged in. And then

00:50:44.100 --> 00:50:49.379
sometimes things get merged in that really like piss people off because like they give a message

00:50:49.379 --> 00:50:55.060
or something. And it's really a balancing game of how many people's like maybe niche problems that

00:50:55.060 --> 00:51:00.340
have we been able to solve because they work with this like, you know, incredibly useful but

00:51:00.340 --> 00:51:05.699
awfully formatted government data set versus a few people need to read messages. So it's really a

00:51:05.699 --> 00:51:09.860
balancing game and I don't think the goal isn't necessarily to make every single user happy

00:51:09.860 --> 00:51:16.260
necessarily, but I think two goals are sort of making things so that we don't lose functionality

00:51:17.300 --> 00:51:23.620
and also making things so that functionality is consistent across packages. Because as you can

00:51:23.620 --> 00:51:28.500
imagine, as the number of people who work on the packages and the functionality of the packages

00:51:28.500 --> 00:51:34.659
grow, sometimes things diverge and it's useful to sort of take a pause and take a look at, okay,

00:51:34.659 --> 00:51:38.979
we have these characteristic things happening in two packages. Like how do we make sure

00:51:38.979 --> 00:51:46.899
this is not super confusing to users? And so issues from people who do data science, like who

00:51:46.899 --> 00:51:54.340
actually do analysis are really helpful. And I will say that hearing from educators who actually

00:51:54.340 --> 00:51:59.780
have to articulate this and teach it to new learners who ask the most critical questions of

